    prompt: 'A language learning app redesigned its onboarding flow 4 weeks ago with the explicit goal of reducing time-to-first-lesson. The redesign shortened the onboarding sequence, removed several goal-setting and personalization steps, and placed the user directly into their first lesson faster. The initial data looks mixed: D1 retention improved from 42% to 48%, which appears positive. But 7-day activation rate — defined as completing 3 or more lessons in the first 7 days — dropped from 31% to 24%. Leadership wants to understand how a design change can simultaneously improve one retention metric and degrade another, and what to do about it.\n\nThis is a D1 vs. D7 paradox: an intervention improved the short-term metric it was optimized for but degraded a longer-term activation metric. The most common explanation is a commitment and investment tradeoff. Onboarding flows that ask users to set goals, state their motivation, and personalize their experience create psychological investment — users who invested time in goal-setting are more likely to return because they feel committed. By removing those steps, the redesign got users to their first lesson faster, which improved the immediate experience (D1), but removed the psychological hook that would bring them back for lessons 2 and 3 in the following days.\n\nA second explanation is first-lesson quality vs. quantity. If the shortened onboarding placed users into a generic starter lesson rather than a personalized one, the quality of the first lesson experience may have dropped. Users who had a mediocre first lesson are less likely to return for a second. This hypothesis predicts that users in the new flow would rate their first lesson lower or abandon it earlier.\n\nA third explanation is a metric definition artifact: D1 retention counts any user who opens the app on day 1, while 7-day activation requires 3 lesson completions. If the new onboarding attracted more casual or low-intent users (because the frictionless entry lowered the bar), D1 might improve due to sheer volume while serious learners — who would have been filtered in by the more demanding original flow — are now diluted by low-intent users who bounce after day 1.\n\nYour task is to distinguish between these explanations using behavioral data and to design an experiment that isolates the commitment/personalization mechanism.',
