    modelAnswer: 'The D1 vs. D7 paradox makes sense once you understand what each metric measures. D1 retention — did the user open the app on day 1 — is driven primarily by the quality of the first session: was the first lesson short, satisfying, and easy to start? The redesign optimized exactly this, and D1 improved from 42% to 48%. But 7-day activation (3+ lessons in 7 days) requires the user to form a reason to come back on days 2, 3, and 4. That reason is commitment — and the redesign removed the goal-setting steps that create it.\n\nGoal-setting in onboarding is not just decoration. When a user states "I want to learn Spanish for my trip in 3 months," they create a concrete anchor that influences return behavior. Removing those steps in the name of speed gets users to their first lesson faster but removes the psychological hook that would bring them back for lesson 2. The D1 improvement is real; the 7-day regression is the cost.\n\nFor the commitment hypothesis I\'d check whether new-flow users score lower on "I have a clear goal for learning this language" in the survey data. If new-flow users report lower goal clarity, the mechanism is confirmed. I\'d also compare mid-lesson abandonment rates between cohorts — if new-flow users abandon the first lesson at a higher rate, the personalization removal produced a worse first lesson match, directly reducing return intent.\n\nFor user composition: I\'d split the new-flow cohort by engagement depth (1 lesson, 2 lessons, 3+ lessons in 7 days) and compare the profile to old-flow equivalents. If the new flow attracted more 1-lesson bouncers while the 3+ lesson segment stayed proportionally similar, low-intent user influx is diluting the metric.\n\nThe experiment should be a 3-arm test: (A) original full onboarding, (B) fast onboarding with no goal-setting, (C) fast onboarding with a 90-second abbreviated goal-setting step. Primary metric: 7-day activation rate. Secondary metric: D1 retention. Run for 3 weeks to capture a full 7-day activation window per cohort. The recommendation is not binary revert vs. keep — if arm C recovers 7-day activation while preserving the D1 lift, that is the path forward.',
